text: Not sure how this collection of beads warranted so many five star reviews.  The container we received looks good from the outside, but actually 'playing' with it was NOT much FUN AT ALL.  Many of the pop beads have holes that are either too large, or pop connectors that are too small, so you can't string the beads without them falling apart.  About one in five beads don't seem to stay connected.  My granddaughter tried and TRIED to make necklaces and bracelets but they kept falling apart and falling off.  She ended up terribly disappointed and so was I.The other HUGE disappointment was that the connectors to be used to decorate rings and bracelets were all quite ugly and non-descript.  They all seem to be terribly dull earthy colors - brown, beige, 'sea sludge' green, etc.  Even the shapes looked more like something gross than decorative.The grandkids did finally find something fun to do with them - tip the jar over and watch all the pieces bounce all over the living room, pick up 'most' of the pieces, and start all over again - then repeat until the jar is only half full and then find something more interesting to do.

text: My children (7 and 9) got this as a gift and I looked at the little booklet that came with it to find what are supposed to be cute quotations from children. What I found was not very subtle, at least to me, anti-father (and thus, anti-family) propaganda. It's subtle enough that most won't notice it consciously, but if one is attuned to what is going on in the world, there is nothing very amusing here.The first one is from Allison, age 4: "If Mommies make babies, and trees make air, then what do we need Daddies for?" Innocent, or a subtle misandric dig and eco-cult worship all rolled into one? From Grace, age 6, in car when Grandpa said "I think we should turn here.": "Don't THINK. Just follow Mommy's directions." Except when the car gets a flat tire, then she'll stand by the side of the road and hope some nice man changes her tire for her. Under her superior supervision of course. Last but not least, Adam age 3 holding a tow truck during show and tell: "This is my hooker." Is this meant for kids to read? Am I supposed to explain to my kids why this is funny? Hey, isn't the politically correct term "sex worker" now? I guess I would have to explain that too.The beads themselves aren't a problem; but I wonder why the manufacturer felt it necessary to place such rubbish in with it.
author: Chaoticmuse
